question:
Give feedback to your teammate by completing the following sentence:

"{{subject}}, I want to work with you because... and I would want to work with you more if..."
subject: Aileen Santos
value:
I want to work with you because you are open to talking about process, you are friendly, welcoming, positive, and you challenge things but are also open to being wrong.

I would want to work with you more if you were accountable around being on time, if you were a bit more receptive to feedback, and if you had a stronger foundation in JavaScript.

Specific feedback:

You would sometimes complete my sentences but you would often say something different than I was going to say.  This put me in a position of having to decide between going along with your thought and never finishing what I started to say, or starting the sentence over again.  In some situations I think that completing the other person's sentences can help communication but I felt that it usually hindered ours.

When I gave you feedback about being on time I feel that you were a bit defensive and dismissive.  You did say thank you, but you also said that you were against the whole idea of being punctual and that I needed to be more sensitive to our levels of privilege.  It's not that I don't think we should have had that conversation - I'm glad we did - but it did feel defensive in the sense that you were trying to justify your lateness.

I think it was inappropriate for you to bring up Nazi Germany when I said that efficiency was a benefit of punctuality.  I felt like you were trying to associate me with Hitler because I value efficiency.

When we were talking about privilege there were times that I didn't feel safe.  I felt like you were waiting for me to say the wrong thing so you could let loose your arsenal.

Technical feedback:

I encourage you to try to be extremely precise when talking about technical things.  I recommend reading the mdn js documentation regularly to get used to the words they use and how precise they are.  This would help develop a better js foundation as well.

One specific weaknesses I noticed was not being clear on the difference between `myFunction` and `myFunction()`.  The first is the function itself and the second is the function being called.

value: You are full of experience and knowledge of things that I want to learn and you are so easy to learn from. You were so patient with my questions and made me feel like they were easy to ask. I learned so much and only because I was able to expose the full breadth of my ignorance! We have the same learning needs, as far as conceptually. This is a conversation that I will take into orienting with my team from now on, because its super helpful to know how to talk about new concepts before we work together. If we work together again, (fingers crossed), I would want to stretch us both into applying the Pomodoro method. Working for 50 minutes and taking a 10 minute break. I think we could've both used timed work intervals to increase our engagement with this project.

value: Steve, working with you went swell, you came in very knowledgeable about the bookstore project as I understand youd worked on it several times before, so you were able to do the majority of the backend implementation almost completely by yourself - which I think was a double-edged sword. You were not very encouraging considering your handle of the material. When we'd make mistakes or we reached a point of confusion you would figuratively snatch the keyboard and take control of the dialog (even after mere seconds of hearing the other team member start navigating), this did not happen every time but it happened enough to notice. You were also a bit stubborn and were almost never open to suggestions made by your teammates. You grew a little antagonistic when bothered by the way things were going, such as when the rest of the team switched to a front-end task and you felt it wasnt worth the time spent. You grew silent, disconnected yourself from the project and would make snide remarks up till we walked away from the front-end and back into your realm of competence. Were all still learning so a little patience goes a long way. Id love to work with you in the future to see some progress in these areas.

subject: SAL
value: Sal, I want to work with you because your communication style naturally meshes so well with my own. This week was an amazing growth experience, and I owe that to how easygoing, flexible, and communicative you were. I also VERY much appreciated you keeping me accountable for my own self-care by making it clear that wasn't a pinch for you, giving me space to make sure that when we were working directly together I could be at 100%. It was also great the way that we planned our mornings around the fact that getting here reliably at 8:30 was a goal for both of us. I felt like we were very mutually supportive in working towards that goal. I'd want to work with you more if you didn't share my weak point regarding project progress. I know that we both could have been a little more proactive about getting the project spec done early and then doing extra work, rather than focusing on individual study and putting off finishing until the end of the week - but I also know via our communication earlier in the week that this was what we both wanted to do, and understand the tradeoff involved. I think that as long as all teammates understand and are intentional about those tradeoffs it's totally okay to make them.
